column6: There is probably no point in updating now, but might as well.
Looks like with current precincts counted, Braun has won. I am updating for whatever it's worth.
The news about Braun being categorized as a "hard democrat" will hurt him so I am lowering his bin.
Flipping toward Braun for several reasons:
Having a hard time with this one, so I tried to break down the different considerations.
So, I'm reluctantly changing my vote.
Shifting my forecast from favoring Braun to Rokita after the last debate on April 30: http://indianadebatecommission.com/live-debate-feed/
Some good background in this article: https://www.politico.com/story/2018/05/01/indiana-senate-republicans-messer-rokita-braun-560708
Messer's DUI's might hurt him.

Rokita had some rub with the Trump Campaign, and an anti-Trump comment by him from 2016 has been unearthed: https://www.indystar.com/story/news/politics/2018/04/18/trump-campaign-rebukes-todd-rokita-over-yard-signs/527332002/

I lean toward Braun for the following reasons: Currently, he is the favorite to win based on prediction markets: https://www.predictit.org/Market/3005/Who-will-win-the-2018-Indiana-Republican-Senate-primary. He's got the funding and endorsements (tied with Lesser on the latter). He has the most Trump-like background. Given Trump's popularity among Republicans, that should be an advantage. Braun doesn't quite have the same name recognition, but he is outspending the other two candidates handily. And despite his outsider background he matches Messer for endorsements (https://ballotpedia.org/United_States_Senate_election_in_Indiana_(May_8,_2018_Republican_primary)).
https://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2018/senate/in/indiana_senate_republican_primary-6523.html

In my travels I have always found the good people of MI, IN, and OH a little different in their electoral calculus - then seem unimpressed or less impressed anyway by rah rah rallys and candidates known for their stump speeches - I offer John Kascich and Dennis Kucinich as my comparison class. Talk about dry toast speakers...
Well that was a quick flip flop. Beats me. Messer is killing in fundraising, more charismatic, better website.
Better fundraising. Better website. More charismatic.
Consensus is putting Rokita in lead, so will just go with Wisdom of the Crowd on this one.

Well the three candidates are more or less evenly matched in terms of money and experience. However, Rokita and Messer apparently hate each other so I suspect they end up spending most of their time attacking on another while Braun is richer and thus able to self fund his own operation and get left alone. As well, according to the one poll (admittedly funded by Rokita) from this year, Rokita is in the lead.

I gave Luke Messer, Todd Rokita, and Mike Braun all the same level probability of winning the Senate seat because they all have the same level of background experience (they are all Congressmen for different Indiana districts) and they are all of the Republican party. I ranked them all relatively low because there is a competitive upcoming republican primary, and it is hard to determine which of the three will pull through at this point. I ranked none of the above higher than all of these candidates, around a 50/50 shot because I believe the current Senator for Indiana, because of his incumbency advantage is more likely to win again but because Indiana can be a typically Republican state, he is also at risk for losing his seat as a democrat.

Messer has better relationships with the political establishment that can help him with less engaged primary voters. Rokita has stronger name recognition with primary voters in my estimate. Braun has personal funds and an interesting story, but that would be more effective in the general in Indiana than breaking through in the primary.
